culum for all children which fused civic as well as imperial ambitions. The book will be of interest to those studying or researching aspects of English domestic imperial culture, especially those concerned with questions of childhood and schooling, citizenship, educational publishing and anglo-British relations. Given that vitriolic debates about the politics of history teaching have endured into the twenty-first century, Citizenship, nation, empire is a timely study of the formative influences that shaped the history curriculum in English schools  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEducational psychologyzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aEducational psychologyzGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aHistoryxStudy and teachingzEngland. 0aHistoryxStudy and teachingzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aHistoryxStudy and teachingzGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aImperialismxHistoryy19th century. 0aImperialismxHistoryy20th century. 0aPatriotismzEnglandy20th century. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aChildhood.  aCitizenship.  aCulture.  aEducation.  aHistory.  aImperialism.  aNational Identity.  aPedagogy.  aPropaganda.1 aYeandle, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2015 eBook-Packagez978311128311140uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779999940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847799999423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847799999/original  a978-3-11-128311-1  Manchester University Press 2015 eBook-Packageb2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles